  // some code here.
})
```

##Promise way - 
```js
PullUserDataFromServer(guid: string): Promise&lt;UserDataEntity&gt;  {
  return this.http.get&lt;UserDataEntity&gt;(this.baseUrl + &quot;api/&quot; + guid).toPromise();
  }
}
```
then,

```js
const userData = await this.PullUserDataFromServer(&quot;some-id&quot;);
// use userData in code.
```

You need to subscribe to your observable created by the http request. The way I would do it would be like this using RxJS declarative approach. Using methods to call a http request is not wrong but it&#39;s the old way of writing Angular Code.

https://www.freecodecamp.org/news/blitz-tips-rxjs-pipe-is-not-a-subscribe-125c89437a2c/

In your service:
//This is an Observable

    pullUserDataFromServer$:Observable&lt;pullUserDataFromServer&gt;;
    this.pullUserDataFromServer$ =  this.http.get&lt;UserDataEntity&gt;(this.baseUrl + &#39;api/&#39; + guid);

Whatever component you want to use the Observable;
//Inject the name of your service here via dependency injection

        import { ISubscription } from &quot;rxjs/Subscription&quot;;
        ....
        private subscription: ISubscription;
        constructor(private nameOfService: NameOfService){}
        
        this.subscription = this.nameOfService.pullUserDataFromServer$.subscribe(//your code here);
    
       ngOnDestroy() {
        this.subscription.unsubscribe();
       }


It&#39;s important for you to unsubscribe if you subscribe manually to avoid memory leaks.

