Most of these concepts are explained very well in [the official documentation][1].

With that out of the way, I&#39;ll try to explain each line, below:

```csharp
public class NotificationBase&lt;T&gt; : NotificationBase where T : class, new()
```
Declares a new class named `NotificationBase&lt;T&gt;` which has a single generic type parameter (`T`). It derives from the class `NotificationBase` (the non-generic version). It has two constraints on the type parameter; it must be a `class` (i.e. reference type, not an enum or other integral type), and it must have a visible empty constructor (as dictated by the `new()` constraint).

```csharp
protected T This;
```
Declares a [protected](https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/csharp/language-reference/keywords/protected) field named `This`. You can use the field in instances of this class and in derived objects.

```csharp
public static implicit operator T(NotificationBase&lt;T&gt; thing) { return thing.This; }
```
Adds an [implicit conversion](https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/csharp/language-reference/operators/user-defined-conversion-operators) from `NotificationBase&lt;T&gt;` to `T`, such that you can do the following (example):
&gt; ```csharp
&gt;NotificationBase&lt;string&gt; myWrappedString = new NotificationBase&lt;string&gt;(&quot;Heya&quot;);
&gt;string myString = myWrappedString;
&gt;// implicit conversion is supported due to the implicit operator declared above.
&gt;```

```csharp
public NotificationBase(T thing = null)
{
    This = (thing == null) ? new T() : thing;
}
```
Declares a public constructor, such that you can create instances of `NotificationBase&lt;T&gt;`. If the input is `null`, the constructor will just `new` up a thing of type `T` (whatever it is, as long as it has an empty constructor). A [ternary operator](https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/csharp/language-reference/operators/conditional-operator) (`predicate ? then : else`) is used to make the code compact and readable when assigning to the `This` field.


  [1]: https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/csharp/programming-guide/generics/generic-classes

